node.text:
National parks have captured our hearts. They honor our history and unite us as a nation. They’re the backdrops for some of our happiest moments. They help us discover who we are, and heal our minds, bodies and souls. National parks are our nation’s greatest love story, but over the years, their bridges, roads and visitor centers have become worn and many are now in disrepair. Our 400+ national parks have an $11.6 billion backlog in maintenance needs, and we’re working to #RebuildOurParks to ensure they remain as extraordinary as when we first fell in love with them. What’s your national park love story? 
Music by Borrtex "Ocean" (@borrtex).

node.text: Experience all that Haleakala National Park has to offer — from sandy beaches and lush forests to amazing sunrises and stunning waterfalls.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Department of the Interior in Shenandoah National Park. May be an image of nature, road and tree.

node.text:
Slowing down saves lives -- especially through parks and public lands where wildlife are just as busy traveling as you are.

Deer, black bear, wild turkey, and a host of other woodland animals call @shenandoahnps home and will regularly cross Skyline Drive in their daily travels. 

Watch out for these animals who may dart across your path, 🐻 bear-ly giving warning. At 35 mph, you'll stand the best chance of a paw-sitive wildlife encounter rather than an unpleasant wildlife experience. If you want a closer look, be sure to pull completely off the road and stay in your vehicle. 

Photo by Valerie Richards (sharetheexperience.org). Photo description: a black bear mom and cub cross a foggy road. #usinterior #teampubliclands

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Department of the Interior in Santa Rosa and San Jacinto Mountains National Monument. May be an image of tree and nature.

node.text:
According to a recent (very real 😉) poll, people overwhelming love paths. Give the people what they want. 

This inviting and colorful path is a section of the Pacific Crest Trail (PCT!) that runs through the @mypubliclands's Santa Rosa and San Jacinto Mountains National Monuments. 

Rising abruptly from the desert floor, the Santa Rosa and San Jacinto Mountains National Monument reaches an elevation of 10,834 feet.  Providing a picturesque backdrop to local communities, visitors can enjoy magnificent palm oases, snow-capped mountains, the #PCT, and wilderness areas.  Its extensive backcountry can be accessed via trails from both the Coachella Valley and the alpine village of Idyllwild. 

Photo by Bob Wick, BLM. Photo description:  A small path leads through a meadow of sagebrush, flowers, and grasses. A pink and blue sunset sky hang above tall mountains in the distance. #usinterior #leavenotrace #california

node.text:
Mid-July at @denalinps in #Alaska means the bright and blazing fireweed is at full bloom! 

Fireweed can be found growing all over Alaska, and is often one of the first plants to return after an area is burned. Fireweed only grows in abundant sunlight and is crowded out by larger plants, but the seeds remain viable in the soil for years and will quickly begin to grow again once fire or some other disturbance restores their access to sunlight. 

There's no question that these iconic stars of summer are gorgeous. The real debate is agreeing on what color they are. Pink? Purple? Please defend your color choice in the comments below. 

Photo by E.Mesner @nationalparkservice. Photo description: Possibly pink and possibly purple fireweed flowers spring up along a gravel road, surrounded by green grass and mountains off in the distance. #usinterior #findyourpark

node.text:
CrocFlix: Are you still watching? 

Continue 
---------- 
Go Back
 
This American crocodile at @evergladesnps has either been streaming for far too long, or it is thermoregulating its body and head temperature by mouth "gaping." We think it’s option 2. 

Different species of reptiles will sometimes sit motionless with their mouth open. It’s not considered aggressive behavior, but thought to be a way to regulate their temperature. 

Although they look similar, alligators are more numerous in #Florida than crocodiles. Gators are darker, have a broader snout, and are typically found in freshwater habitats. Crocodiles, on the other hand, are rare and secretive creatures that inhabit coastal, brackish, and salt-water habitats and are typically lighter colored. 

One of the best ways to view American crocs is to visit the Flamingo section of Everglades National Park. This is where Robert Kramer recently stopped by and they were lucky enough to capture this toothy grin from a safe distance away with a zoom lens on their camera. 

Photo by Robert Kramer @natural_wanders. Photo description: A large crocodile has their mouth open showing all of their teeth and mouth. #usinterior #teampubliclands

node.text:
There's no shortage of majestic scenery at @olympic_nps in #Washington. ⛰️🌼🌲

The forest, coastal, and mountain ecosystems combine to create a spectacular wilderness park and a perfect place for avalanche lily to bloom and thrive. 

Photo by @nationalparkservice. Photo description:  White star shaped flowers blanket a high alpine meadow with trees and rows of snow capped mountains in the background. #usinterior #wildflowers

node.text:
Basking like a badger? 🦡

Badgers have been observed hunting and sun basking on the @_nationalelkrefuge in #Wyoming. Sounds like the perfect mix for a summer afternoon.

While this furry striped tank is not the largest of the North American weasel family—wolverines, river otters and sea otters are bigger—the badger nonetheless seems much larger than its true size.

As these barrels with legs trot towards you, the stocky badger gives off the appearance and attitude that nothing can get in its way. In truth, badgers only measure between 23 to 30 inches and weigh about 15.5 pounds for females and around 20 pounds for males. They're not much bigger than a beagle!

Video by Kari Cieszkiewicz, @usfws. Video description: A fluffy badger lays on a grassy flat surface in the sun. It lifts its head for a moment and then lays back down to rest.

node.text:
Happy 75th Birthday to @mypubliclands! 

Responsible for almost 250 million acres of public land, the BLM  manages resources to best serve the present and future needs of the nation and preserve some of our country’s most stunning and rugged landscapes. 

Photo near Monitor Pass in #California by Bob Wick, BLM. Photo description: Orange flowers cover a desert-like landscape as the sun sets over the mountains in the distance. #usinterior #happybirthday

node.text:
There's so much beauty at @mypubliclands Yaquina Head Outstanding Natural Area in #Oregon! 

Photographer Alyssa Uhen first experienced the magic of Yaquina Head eight years ago as an intern. "The lighthouse, tidepools, and breathtaking views like this one stole my heart the first time I saw it, and my love for this special place has only grown since!" 

Photo by Alyssa Uhen @alyu_22. Photo description: A peninsula covered in green grass and flowers juts out into the ocean with a blue sky and white clouds above. #usinterior #pnw

node.text:
Summer monsoons bring a greater chance for flash floods. These heavy rains increase the depth and speed of water in streams and washes.

A recent flash flood at @ZionNPS demonstrates the danger of these natural events. Ranger Bryan captured this video from their work station. 

So what can you do to stay safe from flash floods?
 
💧 Become familiar with your surroundings

💧 Check the weather forecast

💧 Stop by the visitor center for up to date info

💧 Watch for changing weather and a buildup of clouds

💧 Have a plan. Where's the nearest high ground?
 
The threat of flash floods can seem overwhelming, but monsoon season can also be a beautiful time of year. If you are planning a trip during monsoon season, stay safe during storms. Afterward, take a look outside to see just how much these crucial rains change the landscape. 
 
Videos courtesy of Bryan Schlinkmann, Zion National Park Ranger. Video description: Rain is falling as muddy water, rocks, and debris rush by a work station. Someone is filming from inside a building and recording the flood outside. After the flood water recedes, the videographer goes outside the building and shows the aftermath from the flood event. Machinery can be heard in the background moving rocks and debris from the road. #usinterior #planlikeaparkranger

node.text:
The @mypubliclands's Bisti/De-Na-Zin Wilderness in #NewMexico looks otherworldly. Moon cast shadows on the hoodoos create an unearthly wonderland. 

This rolling landscape of badlands, which offers some of the most unusual scenery found in the Four Corners Region, is isolated and serene. Time and natural elements have etched a fantasy world of strange rock formations made of interbedded sandstone, shale, mudstone, coal, and silt. The weathering of the sandstone forms hoodoos - weathered rock in the form of pinnacles, spires, and cap rocks. These unusual forms can make you feel like you’ve been transported to another planet. 

Photo by Sherman Hogue, BLM. Photo description: Round, egg-shaped rocks are scattered across a desert landscape with a night sky and clouds above. #usinterior #wilderness #leavenotrace

node.text:
Sunrise glamor reflects the morning sky's colors on the rock flats at @usfws's National Key Deer Refuge in #Florida. 

Located 100 miles southwest of Miami, the refuge protects Key deer and is home to the imperiled tropical hardwood hammock habitat. The magic of this place can come in many forms, from the rare species that call it home to the beauty of the upland forests and wetland marsh. 

Photo courtesy of Chad Anderson @_chadanderson_. Photo description: Sunrise on the rock flats at National Key Deer Refuge with a tree rising up out of the rocks. #usinterior #sunrise
